1. PKI Engineer
  Role Summary: A PKI Engineer is the person who builds and manages the system that proves computers and websites 
  are who they say they are. They make sure information traveling across the internet is protected and can’t easily 
  be read or changed by attackers.
Core Responsibilities:
  • Create and manage digital certificates that help prove identity online
  • Set up systems that encrypt information so it stays private
  • Renew or replace certificates before they expire
  • Fix problems when secure connections stop working
  • Make sure the company follows rules for safe encryption
Where PKI Creates Leverage:
  PKI knowledge is the main skill for this job. It helps engineers understand how computers create secret keys, 
  how certificates prove identity, and how systems check if they can trust each other. If something breaks in a
  secure connection, this knowledge helps them figure out exactly why.

2. IAM Engineer
Role Summary:
  An IAM Engineer controls who is allowed to access systems, apps, and data inside a company. Their job is to 
  make sure the right people can get in and the wrong people cannot.
Core Responsibilities:
  • Set up login systems like single sign on and multi factor authentication
  • Manage employee accounts and permissions
  • Decide who should have access to certain systems or files
  • Connect login systems to company apps and tools
  • Watch for risky access like someone getting more permissions than they should
Where PKI Creates Leverage:
  PKI helps IAM engineers create stronger and safer login systems. Certificates can prove that a device or user 
  is trusted. Understanding how certificates and trust work helps prevent fake logins and improves secure
  authentication.

3. Security Operations (SOC / Blue Team)
Role Summary:
  Security Operations teams watch over a company’s systems to detect cyberattacks. They look for unusual 
  activity and respond quickly when something suspicious happens.
Core Responsibilities:
  • Monitor security alerts and system logs
  • Investigate strange activity like unknown logins or malware
  • Respond to security incidents and stop attacks
  • Study how attackers behave so they can catch them faster
  • Improve security monitoring tools
Where PKI Creates Leverage:
  PKI knowledge helps analysts understand how attackers might misuse certificates or encryption to hide 
  their activity. Knowing how trust chains and certificates work helps them spot fake websites, suspicious 
  certificates, or encrypted traffic used by malware.

4. Cloud Security Engineer
Role Summary:
  A Cloud Security Engineer protects systems and data that are stored in cloud platforms like AWS or Azure.
  Their job is to make sure cloud apps, services, and data stay secure.
Core Responsibilities:
  • Protect cloud systems and networks from attacks
  • Set up strong access controls for cloud services
  • Make sure data is encrypted when it moves or is stored
  • Manage keys, secrets, and certificates used by cloud apps
  • Watch for security mistakes or weaknesses in the cloud
Where PKI Creates Leverage:
  PKI helps cloud security engineers protect communication between cloud services. Certificates help
  systems prove who they are before they share information. Understanding PKI makes it easier to secure APIs, 
  websites, and apps running in the cloud.


