  between systems. The trust chain validation lab showed how computers determine whether a certificate should be 
  trusted. Systems check whether the certificate was issued by a trusted certificate authority and verify the chain
  of trust up to a root authority. This process is important in IAM because authentication systems must confirm that 
  a user, device, or service is legitimate before granting access. The career landscape lesson also showed that IAM 
  roles sit at the center of identity, authentication, and access control in cybersecurity. Because modern 
  organizations rely heavily on secure login systems, IAM engineers play a key role in protecting systems from 
  unauthorized access. Overall, IAM feels like the best fit because it combines identity management with the 
  underlying cryptography used in PKI. Understanding how keys, certificates, and trust chains work helps IAM 
  engineers design stronger and more secure authentication systems.

